prospects'\nhave brightened.\u2019\u2019\nVA also quoted predictions that\n4,000.000 more jobs will become\navailable by the end of the year and\nthat unemployment will decrease to\na minimum.\nIn a summary of its own activities\nas well as programs and reports of\nother agencies affecting veterans.\nVA said that it was finally \"over\nthe hump\" in starting programs for\nWorld War II veterans.\nPension Backlog Cut.\nVA reported that it had made the\nfirst reduction since May. 1945. in\nthe backlog of disability pension\ncases awaiting settlement, although\npending cases still numbered 556,000\nat the end of March.\nVeterans awaiting hospitalization\nincreased to 26.000 at the end of\nMarch. VA said it would not cut\ndown the number waiting to get into\nhospitals until new hospitals are\na\\ ailable\nj On that score, however. VA re\nj ported it has awarded no contracts\nfor new hospitals since last Novem\nber and added that \"under the\npresent inflationary market\" the\noutlook for getting bids for hospi\ntals at the prices VA is authorized\nto pay is \"exceedingly dismal.\"\nSummarizing the employment\npicture for veterans as presented\nby other agencies, VA reported:\nVeterans have to be referred to\nmore jobs than nonveterans before\nthey will accept one, according to\nthe USES\nLarge numbers of veterans are\ngoing into the automobile industry\nand other factories now reconvert\ning. but the percentage of veterans\nremains small in the low-wage in\ndustries. such as cotton textiles.\nVeterans appear to be replacing\nwomen in jobs not usually held by\nwomen in peacetime.\n.lobs Without Displacing.\nWhile most industries have been\nable to put. returning veterans back\nat their old jobs without displacing\nnonveterans, difficulties are arising\nin such war-expanded industries as\naircraft and shipbuilding. The\nUSES cited one large West Coast\naircraft plant employing less than\n8.000 workers but with 13.000 vet\nerans with re-employment rights.\nJ In February, for the first time\nsince V-J day, according to the\ncombined survey, the reinstatement\nof veterans in the automobile in\ndustry caused the firing of some\nnonveterans. In some plants, vet\nerans displaced other veterans with\nless seniority.\nThe number of re-employment\ncases involving veterans which re\nquired court actions increased from\n29 in late January to 67 on April 8.\nwhile the number of cases in the\nhands of United States attorneys\nincreased from 10.3 to 327. according\nto selective service.\n120 More Draft Aides\nReceive Honors Tuesday\nSelective .service medals and cer\ntificates will be given to a second\ngroup of District men at a cere\nmony in the Departmental Audi\ntorium at 8 p.nt. Tuesday\nCommissioner John Russell Young\nwill make the presentations, and\nSelective Service Director Lewis B\nHershey is expected to speak.\nAwards authorized by Congress\nwill go to 120 men who served on\ndraft and appeal boards, as Govern\nment appeal agents, re-employment\ncommitteemen and draft board phy\nsicians who were not eligible when\nthe awards were presented in Febiu\nary because at that time thev had\n\u2022served less than two years. Included\nut those to be given awards are a\ngroup of men who served in selective\nservice for a year or more before en\ntering the armed forces themselves\nAnother set of awards, given by\nDistrict Selective Service Director\nWilliam E. Leahy, will go to 225\nvolunteers who helped men fill out\ntheir draft questionnaires early in\nthe war. The local awards will be\nsent to 150 members of the Ameri\ncan Legion who served as clerical\nassistants to doctors examining draft\nregistrants at local hospitals. Dis\ntrict Selective Service headquarters\nannounced.\nLOST.\nf uvSfi\u2014CL,J\u2019 between Giant store and\n\u00bb\u00abEMSe^' keeps* ke^jRe\nSPtVJ&e.V*** f?lrt\u2018n? 11 \u00ab=lost Sundiy\nEast'?laP i\"\": left in taxi Sunday\nCaHCT SMXTH /aa.HntTfi15- n w~ R,J5Vd-'\n&S? SSp\" w\u00abhd buckfe EU&erHSS\na own town. Re